<figcaption id="mntl-figure-caption_2-0" class="comp mntl-figure-caption text-utility-100 figure-article-caption"> <span class="figure-article-caption-owner">Allrecipes / Grace Elkus</span>
</figcaption></figure>
<span class="heading-toc" id="toc-test-kitchen-tips"></span><h2 id="mntl-sc-block_15-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block allrecipes-sc-block-heading mntl-sc-block-heading"> <span class="mntl-sc-block-heading__text text-title-300"> Test Kitchen Tips </span> </h2>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_16-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> “This is a no-fuss recipe,” according to culinary producer Nicole McLaughlin (a.k.a. <a href="https://www.allrecipes.com/author/nicole-mclaughlin/" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">NicoleMcMom</a>). “I love a plain, simple banana bread.” Here are a few banana bread tips and tricks from the expert:&nbsp;
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_17-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<ul id="mntl-sc-block_18-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> <li>Avoid choosing green bananas. Instead opt for ripe bananas that are yellow with a few brown spots. </li><li>The best and easiest way to mash bananas? With a fork! </li><li>Stir just until the dry ingredients are incorporated. Overmixing can result in dense, tough bread.</li><li>Start checking a few minutes early; the bread is done when a toothpick comes out with moist crumbs, not wet batter.</li><li>The recipe calls for a 9x5 loaf pan, but it’s fine if you have something smaller – just increase the cook time by a few minutes. </li>
</ul>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_19-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<span class="heading-toc" id="toc-how-to-store-banana-bread"></span><h2 id="mntl-sc-block_20-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block allrecipes-sc-block-heading mntl-sc-block-heading"> <span class="mntl-sc-block-heading__text text-title-300"> How to Store Banana Bread </span> </h2>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_21-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> Banana bread will stay fresh for about 4 days at room temperature when stored properly. To keep it moist, place a paper towel in the bottom of an airtight container or zip-top bag. Set the cooled loaf on top, then cover it with another paper towel before sealing tightly. The paper towels absorb excess moisture, preventing sogginess while keeping the banana bread soft. Store in a cool, dry place at room temperature.
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_22-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_23-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> Avoid refrigerating banana bread, as it can dry out more quickly in the fridge.
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_24-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<span class="heading-toc" id="toc-can-you-freeze-banana-bread"></span><h2 id="mntl-sc-block_25-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block allrecipes-sc-block-heading mntl-sc-block-heading"> <span class="mntl-sc-block-heading__text text-title-300"> Can You Freeze Banana Bread? </span> </h2>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_26-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> Yes, banana bread freezes very well! It will keep for 2 to 4 months while maintaining good quality. Wrap the cooled loaf tightly in plastic wrap, then add a layer of aluminum foil. You can also freeze individual slices if you don’t plan to thaw the whole loaf at once. To thaw, let the bread sit at room temperature while still wrapped to retain moisture. Individual slices can be warmed briefly in the microwave or toaster oven.
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_27-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<span class="heading-toc" id="toc-allrecipes-community-tips-and-praise"></span><h2 id="mntl-sc-block_28-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block allrecipes-sc-block-heading mntl-sc-block-heading"> <span class="mntl-sc-block-heading__text text-title-300"> Allrecipes Community Tips and Praise </span> </h2>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_29-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> &#34;I&#39;ve made several banana bread recipes here and I always come back to this one,&#34; says SOULWOLF. &#34; It is a wonderful standard recipe that you can build upon and customize to your liking.  I generally use about 5 medium size bananas but have used a little as three and it still came out good.&#34;
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_30-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_31-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> &#34;Simple recipe that never fails,&#34; according to Jheley. &#34;We Love it! It&#39;s now my go-to! I&#39;ve added nuts, vanilla, cinnamon and chocolate chips (not all at once, but as variations just to experiment a bit and they&#39;ve all been great) I&#39;ve also made them as muffins and it literally never fails!&#34;
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_32-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_33-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> &#34;This turned out so yummy,&#34; raves Britt Pfaff. &#34;I&#39;m pretty sure this is the recipe I use every year but always forget! The only change I made was adding vanilla extract and walnuts. I doubled the recipe to make two loaves and my 6-year-old daughter loved making it with me!&#34;
</p>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_34-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-adslot mntl-block"></div>
<p id="mntl-sc-block_35-0" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html"> Editorial contributions by <a href="https://www.allrecipes.com/author/corey-williams/" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1"><strong>Corey Williams</strong></a>
</p></div></div>
